display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk }=\mathbb {Z}[\mathrm {i}]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
<fr:li>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk =\mathbb {Q}(\sqrt {2})]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk }=\mathbb {Z}[\sqrt {2}]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
<fr:li>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk =\mathbb {Q}(\sqrt {5})]]></fr:tex>. Then the minimal polynomial of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sqrt {5}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\sqrt {5}}(x)=x^{2}-x-1]]></fr:tex>. This means that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk }=\mathbb {Z}[\varphi ]]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi =(1+\sqrt {5})/2]]></fr:tex> is the golden ratio.</fr:li></fr:ol>
 
   
